# Cursor AI Rules for TVT Project

## Git commits (mandatory)

- For any change under `src/`, `tests/`, or `tests/samples/` (or other tracked sample/fixture trees), follow **`docs/GIT_COMMIT_POLICY.md`** end-to-end: subject/body, coherent commits, no secrets, `cargo fmt` / `cargo clippy` / `cargo test` before push, and the Paperclip **`Co-Authored-By: Paperclip <noreply@paperclip.ing>`** trailer when the commit is produced by an automated Paperclip agent run.

## Testing Enforcement
- ALWAYS run `cargo test` after making any code changes
- Write tests for every new feature before implementing it (TDD approach)
- Ensure all tests pass before committing changes
- Use `cargo test --verbose` to see detailed test output

## Code Quality
- Follow Rust naming conventions (snake_case for functions/variables, PascalCase for types)
- Use `cargo clippy` to check for linting issues
- Use `cargo fmt` to format code consistently
- Add documentation comments for all public functions and types

## Project Structure
- Keep tests in the `tests/` directory for integration tests
- Use `#[cfg(test)]` modules for unit tests within source files
- Follow the established module structure: main.rs, analyzer.rs, hasher.rs, etc.

## Error Handling
- Use `anyhow::Result<T>` for error propagation
- Provide meaningful error messages with context
- Handle all possible error cases explicitly

## Performance
- Use parallel processing where appropriate (Rayon, Crossbeam)
- Profile code with `cargo bench` for performance-critical sections
- Monitor memory usage and avoid unnecessary allocations
